docs.lead_paragraph: Rohit Prasad, a senior Amazon executive, had an urgent message for ninth and 10th graders at Dearborn STEM Academy, a public school in Boston’s Roxbury neighborhood.

docs.lead_paragraph: Manny Medina, the chief executive of a Seattle-based artificial intelligence sales company, doesn’t mind repeating himself. It comes with the territory, after all. That tolerance proved convenient this year as he faced the same question innumerable times.

docs.abstract: Over 700 workers in Coventry joined a union and are seeking recognition for it to negotiate with the company, known for its resistance to organized labor.
docs.snippet: Over 700 workers in Coventry joined a union and are seeking recognition for it to negotiate with the company, known for its resistance to organized labor.
docs.lead_paragraph: Last summer, as Britain’s inflation rate reached 10 percent, Amazon gave its workers there a pay raise. At a warehouse in Coventry, in the Midlands of England, the offer was for an extra 50 pence (about 63 cents) an hour, or about 5 percent.

headline.main: At a British Amazon Warehouse, a Union Bid Surges, Then Stalls
headline.print_headline: A Union Bid at Amazon Stalls in Britain

docs.abstract: The secretary of state’s talks with Xi Jinping raised hopes that the world’s two biggest economies might stabilize relations, but the big challenges were not resolved.

docs.lead_paragraph: Worries about China’s economic recovery sent stocks and U.S. futures lower on Tuesday morning, despite a promising meeting on Monday between the country’s top leader, Xi Jinping, and Secretary of State Antony Blinken in Beijing.

headline.main: Business Lessons From Blinken’s Trip to China

docs.abstract: The lawsuit is the first time that the Federal Trade Commission under its chair, Lina Khan, has taken Amazon to court.
docs.snippet: The lawsuit is the first time that the Federal Trade Commission under its chair, Lina Khan, has taken Amazon to court.
docs.lead_paragraph: The Federal Trade Commission sued Amazon on Wednesday, accusing it of illegally inducing consumers to sign up for its Prime service and then hindering them from canceling the subscription, in the most aggressive action against the company to date by the agency’s chair, Lina Khan.

headline.main: F.T.C. Accuses Amazon of Tricking Users Into Subscribing to Prime
headline.print_headline: Amazon Traps Users in Service, Regulator Says

docs.abstract: The F.T.C. chair shot to fame six years ago after publishing an academic article that the company needed to be contained. Legal experts wonder if that time has come.
docs.snippet: The F.T.C. chair shot to fame six years ago after publishing an academic article that the company needed to be contained. Legal experts wonder if that time has come.
docs.lead_paragraph: In 2017, Lina Khan, then a 29-year-old law student, shot to fame with an academic article about why Amazon should be contained. Cutting against prevailing trends in antitrust law, Khan argued that the e-commerce giant was unfairly dominating huge swaths of the American economy.

headline.main: Lina Khan Raises the Heat on Amazon

docs.abstract: Boots Riley’s surreal satire about a teenage giant and an authoritarian superhero is a larger-than-life achievement.
docs.snippet: Boots Riley’s surreal satire about a teenage giant and an authoritarian superhero is a larger-than-life achievement.
docs.lead_paragraph: Boots Riley doesn’t aim small. In his 2018 directorial debut film, “Sorry to Bother You,” the frontman of the revolution-minded hip-hop group the Coup created a chaotic fantasia of corporate exploitation that strained at the seams of its indie-movie clothing.

headline.print_headline: Artful Propaganda In a Big Package
